00:01:31.232 --> 00:01:32.690 align:middle line:84%
I interviewed you
a couple of years

00:01:32.690 --> 00:01:35.590 align:middle line:84%
to go with your wonderful book
"The Millionaire's Notebook."

00:01:35.590 --> 00:01:36.390 align:middle line:90%
>> Thank you.

00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:41.050 align:middle line:84%
>> And one of the things is
that you weren't left any money.

00:01:41.050 --> 00:01:44.050 align:middle line:10%
As a matter of fact, before
you were a millionaire,

00:01:44.050 --> 00:01:45.770 align:middle line:10%
you were a complete failure.

00:01:45.770 --> 00:01:46.570 align:middle line:10%
>> Exactly.

00:01:46.570 --> 00:01:49.240 align:middle line:10%
>> You want to tell people
about some of the jobs you had

00:01:49.240 --> 00:01:52.220 align:middle line:10%
in case anyone out there is
worried about being a failure?

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:53.020 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:01:53.020 --> 00:01:55.148 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't so much
a particular job,

00:01:55.148 --> 00:01:56.440 align:middle line:90%
it was how many I went through.

00:01:56.440 --> 00:02:00.070 align:middle line:84%
I went through nine
jobs in six years.

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:01.630 align:middle line:84%
When I was in my
third job, which

00:02:01.630 --> 00:02:05.320 align:middle line:84%
was working for an insurance
company, my boss-- a Harvard

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:08.952 align:middle line:84%
MBA-- called me into his
office and said, Steve,

00:02:08.952 --> 00:02:10.660 align:middle line:84%
you're the single
greatest disappointment

00:02:10.660 --> 00:02:12.290 align:middle line:90%
in my entire career.

00:02:12.290 --> 00:02:14.350 align:middle line:84%
You will never
succeed in marketing.

00:02:14.350 --> 00:02:16.210 align:middle line:84%
You have 20 minutes to
clean out your desk.

00:02:16.210 --> 00:02:17.620 align:middle line:90%
And that was job number three.

00:02:17.620 --> 00:02:20.650 align:middle line:84%
I had six more jobs to lose
in the next four years.

00:02:20.650 --> 00:02:22.570 align:middle line:84%
And at 23, I really
believed him.

00:02:22.570 --> 00:02:24.040 align:middle line:84%
I thought, I'm
destined to failure.

00:02:24.040 --> 00:02:26.200 align:middle line:84%
I can't keep a job for
more than a few months.

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:28.420 align:middle line:84%
I was earning less than
half the national average,

00:02:28.420 --> 00:02:30.760 align:middle line:90%
as far as income goes.

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:34.720 align:middle line:84%
Yet on job number 10, we
started a company from scratch--

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:36.010 align:middle line:90%
myself and one other partner.

00:02:36.010 --> 00:02:38.980 align:middle line:90%
He had $5,000, I had an idea.

00:02:38.980 --> 00:02:42.460 align:middle line:84%
And we've turned it into 14
multimillion-dollar companies

00:02:42.460 --> 00:02:45.490 align:middle line:84%
with over $1 billion
and a half in sales.

00:02:45.490 --> 00:02:48.430 align:middle line:84%
And looking back-- that
was over 20 years ago.

00:02:48.430 --> 00:02:52.270 align:middle line:84%
Looking back, I
began to explore what

00:02:52.270 --> 00:02:54.790 align:middle line:84%
made the difference
between the first nine jobs

00:02:54.790 --> 00:02:56.350 align:middle line:90%
and job number 10.

00:02:56.350 --> 00:02:59.170 align:middle line:84%
And it was basically 15
particular strategies

00:02:59.170 --> 00:03:01.870 align:middle line:84%
that began to take
hold in my life

00:03:01.870 --> 00:03:04.510 align:middle line:84%
and really have hold
on that 10th job,

00:03:04.510 --> 00:03:07.630 align:middle line:84%
and enabled me and my
partners to achieve

00:03:07.630 --> 00:03:11.020 align:middle line:84%
every one of our impossible
dreams professionally.

00:03:11.020 --> 00:03:13.060 align:middle line:84%
And at first I
thought, well, I'm

00:03:13.060 --> 00:03:15.820 align:middle line:84%
probably the only one in the
world that's discovered this.

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:18.940 align:middle line:84%
And then I met up with
a high school classmate.

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:22.408 align:middle line:84%
I went to school with a kid
who was a D minus student.

00:03:22.408 --> 00:03:24.700 align:middle line:84%
He and I sat next to each
other at every football game,

00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:25.500 align:middle line:90%
as you know.

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:27.640 align:middle line:90%
And he was in the band.

00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:29.590 align:middle line:90%
I was in the color guard.

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:31.938 align:middle line:84%
Our combined weight was
about 220 pounds, most of--

00:03:31.938 --> 00:03:32.980 align:middle line:90%
>> You were nerds, right?

00:03:32.980 --> 00:03:33.880 align:middle line:90%
>> We were nerds.

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:35.777 align:middle line:90%
Most of our weight was acne.

00:03:35.777 --> 00:03:37.360 align:middle line:84%
The whole time we
were in high school,

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:40.030 align:middle line:84%
we never asked a single girl
out from our high school,

00:03:40.030 --> 00:03:41.530 align:middle line:90%
because we were so shy.

00:03:41.530 --> 00:03:43.160 align:middle line:90%
And nobody knew who we were.

00:03:43.160 --> 00:03:45.820 align:middle line:84%
And yet 20 years later, when
I met up with Steven Spielberg

00:03:45.820 --> 00:03:48.610 align:middle line:84%
at a restaurant, we
began to compare notes.

00:03:48.610 --> 00:03:50.650 align:middle line:84%
And we found out we did
the exact same things.

00:03:50.650 --> 00:03:53.560 align:middle line:84%
He did them in film, I
did them in business.

00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:56.020 align:middle line:84%
Later, I met a guy who became
one of my closest friends,

00:03:56.020 --> 00:03:57.850 align:middle line:90%
a guy named Gene.

00:03:57.850 --> 00:04:01.420 align:middle line:84%
Gene graduated 299 out
of a class of 301--

00:04:01.420 --> 00:04:03.460 align:middle line:84%
said the only people
that were lower than him

00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:06.040 align:middle line:84%
on the totem pole couldn't
write their own names.

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:08.110 align:middle line:84%
But got a track
scholarship to SC.

00:04:08.110 --> 00:04:09.310 align:middle line:90%
Lost it his freshman year.

00:04:09.310 --> 00:04:11.650 align:middle line:84%
Flunked out of college
his freshman year.

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:13.840 align:middle line:84%
Was sleeping on park
benches in Santa Monica.

00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:16.878 align:middle line:84%
His first job was selling
blankets door to door.

00:04:16.878 --> 00:04:18.670 align:middle line:84%
Most of us don't buy
our blankets that way,

00:04:18.670 --> 00:04:20.142 align:middle line:90%
so he failed at that one.

00:04:20.142 --> 00:04:22.600 align:middle line:84%
But he went on to become the
single most successful writer,

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:25.120 align:middle line:84%
director, producer in
television history,

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:27.110 align:middle line:84%
because he had a batting
average of 1,000.

00:04:27.110 --> 00:04:29.350 align:middle line:90%
100% of his shows were big hits.

00:04:29.350 --> 00:04:31.420 align:middle line:90%
His name became Michael Landon.

00:04:31.420 --> 00:04:33.460 align:middle line:84%
And as we compared
notes again, Mike

00:04:33.460 --> 00:04:35.380 align:middle line:84%
did the same thing
Steve and I did.

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:36.580 align:middle line:90%
Then I met Lee Iacocca.

00:04:36.580 --> 00:04:37.570 align:middle line:90%
Same thing.

00:04:37.570 --> 00:04:38.770 align:middle line:90%
>> What did you do?

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:41.260 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, we began
using these strategies.

00:04:41.260 --> 00:04:44.070 align:middle line:84%
Basically, I compare
people to a rocket.

00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:45.672 align:middle line:84%
We're like the Saturn
V rocket, which

00:04:45.672 --> 00:04:47.380 align:middle line:84%
has these five massive
engines, but we've

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:49.630 align:middle line:90%
got seven massive engines.

00:04:49.630 --> 00:04:51.820 align:middle line:84%
But we're all held down
to the launching pad

00:04:51.820 --> 00:04:53.623 align:middle line:90%
by six giant chains.

00:04:53.623 --> 00:04:55.540 align:middle line:84%
And what all of us had
done-- those of us that

00:04:55.540 --> 00:04:57.123 align:middle line:84%
were achieving our
impossible dreams--

00:04:57.123 --> 00:04:59.050 align:middle line:84%
is we learned what
those chains were, we

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:00.760 align:middle line:84%
cut every one of
those chains, and then

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:02.050 align:middle line:90%
we simply ignited the engines.

00:05:02.050 --> 00:05:04.570 align:middle line:84%
We learned what the engines
were and ignited them.

00:05:04.570 --> 00:05:08.950 align:middle line:84%
And as I began to study
people throughout history--

00:05:08.950 --> 00:05:11.230 align:middle line:84%
people like Clara Barton,
who created the American Red

00:05:11.230 --> 00:05:15.790 align:middle line:84%
Cross, Helen Keller, even Mother
Teresa, who had some impossible

00:05:15.790 --> 00:05:19.570 align:middle line:84%
dreams that she achieved,
Henry Ford, Thomas Edison, Bill

00:05:19.570 --> 00:05:22.150 align:middle line:90%
Gates, Sam Walton.

00:05:22.150 --> 00:05:24.630 align:middle line:84%
They all had these
impossible dreams,

00:05:24.630 --> 00:05:27.250 align:middle line:84%
and like everybody else, were
held down to their launching

00:05:27.250 --> 00:05:28.330 align:middle line:90%
pad by these six chains.

00:05:28.330 --> 00:05:30.400 align:middle line:84%
But they learned how
to cut the chains.

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:33.340 align:middle line:84%
They learned how to ignite
these seven massive engines.

00:05:33.340 --> 00:05:35.290 align:middle line:84%
And then achieving
their impossible dreams

00:05:35.290 --> 00:05:39.370 align:middle line:84%
became almost a routine rather
than an exception for them.

00:05:39.370 --> 00:05:41.290 align:middle line:84%
And that's what the
book focuses on.

00:05:41.290 --> 00:05:43.623 align:middle line:84%
>> But the one thing-- again,
there were many different.

00:05:43.623 --> 00:05:46.300 align:middle line:84%
I'd like to go through
some of the changes here.

00:05:46.300 --> 00:05:48.850 align:middle line:84%
But the first one that
comes to my mind--

00:05:48.850 --> 00:05:50.720 align:middle line:84%
although there are
quite a few of them--

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:53.990 align:middle line:84%
is that we're afraid
we're going to fail.

00:05:53.990 --> 00:05:55.255 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:05:55.255 --> 00:05:57.130 align:middle line:84%
Fear of failure is
actually the second chain.

00:05:57.130 --> 00:05:59.920 align:middle line:84%
The first chain that
a person has to cut

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:02.500 align:middle line:84%
is, we've been programmed
for mediocrity.

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:04.300 align:middle line:84%
We graduate from high
school, and if we

00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:07.360 align:middle line:84%
weren't the homecoming king,
straight-A student, or the star

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:09.580 align:middle line:84%
quarterback, we think
of ourselves as average,

00:06:09.580 --> 00:06:11.710 align:middle line:84%
a little bit above,
or a little bit below.

00:06:11.710 --> 00:06:14.350 align:middle line:84%
And from that point on,
we only set average goals,

00:06:14.350 --> 00:06:15.850 align:middle line:90%
because we don't want to fail.

00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:18.622 align:middle line:84%
>> And we hear this
programming as we grow up.

00:06:18.622 --> 00:06:20.080 align:middle line:84%
Like, "Who do you
think you are?"--

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:20.390 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:20.830 align:middle line:90%
We hear--

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:21.170 align:middle line:90%
>> --type of things.

00:06:21.170 --> 00:06:21.550 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:06:21.550 --> 00:06:22.860 align:middle line:90%
But look at how we're judged.

00:06:22.860 --> 00:06:23.710 align:middle line:90%
We're not popular.

00:06:23.710 --> 00:06:25.312 align:middle line:84%
So we're not only
judged by our peers

00:06:25.312 --> 00:06:27.520 align:middle line:84%
and our teachers and our
parents by these three false

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:29.710 align:middle line:84%
standards-- grades,
athletics, and popularity--

00:06:29.710 --> 00:06:31.790 align:middle line:90%
but we judge ourselves that way.

00:06:31.790 --> 00:06:34.930 align:middle line:84%
And so we really think that
the people who achieve--

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:36.790 align:middle line:90%
like Spielberg or Iacocca--

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:39.430 align:middle line:84%
or Oprah Winfrey is
another one that I studied.

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:41.830 align:middle line:84%
We think that they're
exceptional people,

00:06:41.830 --> 00:06:43.540 align:middle line:90%
that they're extraordinary.

00:06:43.540 --> 00:06:46.360 align:middle line:84%
Well, they achieve
extraordinary outcomes,

00:06:46.360 --> 00:06:48.690 align:middle line:84%
but their IQs aren't
off the charts.

00:06:48.690 --> 00:06:50.980 align:middle line:90%
They're not Einsteins.

00:06:50.980 --> 00:06:52.438 align:middle line:84%
Their family
backgrounds-- they all

00:06:52.438 --> 00:06:54.522 align:middle line:84%
didn't grow up with a
silver spoon in their mouth.

00:06:54.522 --> 00:06:56.860 align:middle line:84%
In fact, usually, they've
had pretty hard circumstances

00:06:56.860 --> 00:06:57.700 align:middle line:90%
growing up.

00:06:57.700 --> 00:07:00.160 align:middle line:84%
But they learned some
very specific strategies

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:01.930 align:middle line:84%
and techniques and
begin to implement

00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:04.870 align:middle line:90%
those in their daily lives.

00:07:04.870 --> 00:07:07.840 align:middle line:90%
Fear of failure is a huge chain.

00:07:07.840 --> 00:07:10.985 align:middle line:84%
We learn real early in
life that failure hurts,

00:07:10.985 --> 00:07:12.610 align:middle line:84%
so we do everything
we can to avoid it,

00:07:12.610 --> 00:07:15.820 align:middle line:84%
including setting very
achievable, reachable goals.

00:07:15.820 --> 00:07:17.200 align:middle line:84%
In fact, the world
tells us that.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:19.330 align:middle line:84%
Even motivational
speakers say, only

00:07:19.330 --> 00:07:21.307 align:middle line:84%
set achievable, reachable
goals, otherwise

00:07:21.307 --> 00:07:22.390 align:middle line:90%
you'll frustrate yourself.

00:07:22.390 --> 00:07:23.530 align:middle line:90%
>> But you don't say that.

00:07:23.530 --> 00:07:24.010 align:middle line:90%
>> No.

00:07:24.010 --> 00:07:25.000 align:middle line:90%
>> You say shoot for the moon.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:25.150 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:07:25.150 --> 00:07:26.350 align:middle line:90%
You set impossible goals.

00:07:26.350 --> 00:07:28.690 align:middle line:84%
Every single dream that I
have is an impossible dream.

00:07:28.690 --> 00:07:30.490 align:middle line:90%
Same with Steven Spielberg.

00:07:30.490 --> 00:07:34.030 align:middle line:84%
Steve does not know how to
create a model of a dinosaur.

00:07:34.030 --> 00:07:37.050 align:middle line:84%
If you put a gun to his head
and say, give me a dinosaur,

00:07:37.050 --> 00:07:39.915 align:middle line:84%
and you've got 10 years
to build a good one,

00:07:39.915 --> 00:07:41.540 align:middle line:84%
you'd have to shoot
him after 10 years.

00:07:41.540 --> 00:07:42.460 align:middle line:90%
He couldn't do it.

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:44.680 align:middle line:84%
If you put a gun to his
head and say, give me

00:07:44.680 --> 00:07:47.920 align:middle line:84%
two great computerized special
effects, he couldn't do it.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:49.810 align:middle line:84%
Couldn't give you two,
much less hundreds

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:51.310 align:middle line:90%
that he needs in a film.

00:07:51.310 --> 00:07:53.650 align:middle line:84%
And yet he has an
impossible dream

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:55.810 align:middle line:84%
of creating a film that
is so realistic that, when

00:07:55.810 --> 00:07:58.890 align:middle line:84%
you see those dinosaurs, and you
hear their feet hit the ground,

00:07:58.890 --> 00:07:59.690 align:middle line:90%
and--

00:07:59.690 --> 00:08:01.448 align:middle line:90%
I mean, they'll terrify you.

00:08:01.448 --> 00:08:02.740 align:middle line:90%
Because it's really believable.

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:04.780 align:middle line:84%
And you worry about
the kids about

00:08:04.780 --> 00:08:07.840 align:middle line:84%
to be caught in the
kitchen, and all that stuff.

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:09.640 align:middle line:84%
How did he achieve
that impossible dream?

00:08:09.640 --> 00:08:11.560 align:middle line:84%
Well, he ignited
engine number three,

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:13.300 align:middle line:84%
which we'll get into
on the next show.

00:08:13.300 --> 00:08:14.920 align:middle line:84%
But engine number
three allowed him

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:18.805 align:middle line:84%
to recruit Stan Winston to make
his models and industrial light

00:08:18.805 --> 00:08:20.362 align:middle line:90%
and magic to make his effects.

00:08:20.362 --> 00:08:21.820 align:middle line:84%
And as a result of
that, he gave us

00:08:21.820 --> 00:08:24.730 align:middle line:84%
a film that was very
believable, that we really

00:08:24.730 --> 00:08:26.950 align:middle line:84%
got into once we
were in the theater.

00:08:26.950 --> 00:08:29.710 align:middle line:10%
And that's how it is in
life, whether your dreams are

00:08:29.710 --> 00:08:33.070 align:middle line:10%
to have a great marriage,
to be a great parent,

00:08:33.070 --> 00:08:36.759 align:middle line:10%
or to achieve phenomenal
outcomes in business

00:08:36.759 --> 00:08:37.559 align:middle line:10%
or in your career.

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:39.789 align:middle line:10%
Wherever those
dreams lie, you can

00:08:39.789 --> 00:08:42.822 align:middle line:10%
achieve those dreams
when you cut the chains

00:08:42.822 --> 00:08:43.780 align:middle line:10%
and ignite the engines.

00:08:43.780 --> 00:08:46.045 align:middle line:84%
And fear of failure
is one of the ones

00:08:46.045 --> 00:08:47.170 align:middle line:90%
you have to cut real early.

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:49.240 align:middle line:90%
We give two techniques.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:53.240 align:middle line:10%
If you use those techniques,
you will cut it every time

00:08:53.240 --> 00:08:55.145 align:middle line:10%
it raises its head,
and fear of failure

00:08:55.145 --> 00:08:56.770 align:middle line:10%
will never again have
to hold you down.

00:08:56.770 --> 00:08:57.830 align:middle line:10%
>> What are they?

00:08:57.830 --> 00:08:58.630 align:middle line:10%
>> OK.

00:08:58.630 --> 00:09:02.080 align:middle line:10%
Well, number one, you
have to understand fear.

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:03.610 align:middle line:90%
There's good fear and bad fear.

00:09:03.610 --> 00:09:06.250 align:middle line:90%
Most fear is bad fear.

00:09:06.250 --> 00:09:08.710 align:middle line:84%
Good fear keeps you
alive on the freeway--

00:09:08.710 --> 00:09:10.510 align:middle line:90%
keeps you alert.

00:09:10.510 --> 00:09:11.920 align:middle line:90%
It keeps pilots alive.

00:09:11.920 --> 00:09:14.290 align:middle line:84%
It keeps doctors from
making major mistakes.

00:09:14.290 --> 00:09:16.560 align:middle line:90%
Bad fear paralyzes you.

00:09:16.560 --> 00:09:18.520 align:middle line:90%
It keeps you from taking action.

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:21.190 align:middle line:84%
And throughout life, we
have a lot of this bad fear,

00:09:21.190 --> 00:09:23.210 align:middle line:84%
so we don't take the
action we need to take.

00:09:23.210 --> 00:09:26.470 align:middle line:84%
So the first thing we do is, we
show a technique that shows you

00:09:26.470 --> 00:09:30.290 align:middle line:84%
how to assess the true
perspective of something you

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:31.090 align:middle line:90%
fear.

00:09:31.090 --> 00:09:33.160 align:middle line:84%
What's the absolute
worst that can happen?

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:34.720 align:middle line:90%
And you write that down--

00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:35.743 align:middle line:90%
if you fail.

00:09:35.743 --> 00:09:37.660 align:middle line:84%
Then we have you write
down, on the other side

00:09:37.660 --> 00:09:40.300 align:middle line:84%
of the table, what's the best
thing that's going to happen

00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:41.510 align:middle line:90%
if there is no failure?

00:09:41.510 --> 00:09:42.927 align:middle line:84%
What's the best
thing you're going

00:09:42.927 --> 00:09:44.410 align:middle line:90%
to achieve in that situation?

00:09:44.410 --> 00:09:47.180 align:middle line:10%
You go, wow, look at what
I can do if I don't fail.

00:09:47.180 --> 00:09:49.572 align:middle line:84%
Then we say, OK, what's
the likely scenario?

00:09:49.572 --> 00:09:51.280 align:middle line:84%
Well, the likely
scenario is, there might

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:52.405 align:middle line:90%
be a little bit of failure.

00:09:52.405 --> 00:09:54.000 align:middle line:84%
Here are some
consequences of that.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.290 align:middle line:84%
And I might not hit
this kind of success,

00:09:56.290 --> 00:09:57.640 align:middle line:90%
but I'm going to hit in between.

00:09:57.640 --> 00:09:59.723 align:middle line:84%
Well, even when you look
at that, all of a sudden,

00:09:59.723 --> 00:10:01.480 align:middle line:90%
the failure isn't that big.

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:03.200 align:middle line:84%
It used to be great
big in your mind.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:05.117 align:middle line:84%
Now, you've brought it
right into perspective.

00:10:05.117 --> 00:10:06.075 align:middle line:90%
You say, you know what?

00:10:06.075 --> 00:10:07.670 align:middle line:84%
That's a risk I'm
willing to take.

00:10:07.670 --> 00:10:09.170 align:middle line:84%
And that's in my
marriage, whatever.

00:10:09.170 --> 00:10:12.460 align:middle line:84%
A lot of times, women
will be afraid to confront

00:10:12.460 --> 00:10:14.710 align:middle line:84%
their husbands on something
that's really hurting them

00:10:14.710 --> 00:10:16.668 align:middle line:84%
because they think, oh,
he'll just ridicule me.

00:10:16.668 --> 00:10:17.500 align:middle line:90%
He'll say no.

00:10:17.500 --> 00:10:17.680 align:middle line:90%
This--

00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:18.490 align:middle line:90%
>> Or he'll leave.

00:10:18.490 --> 00:10:19.300 align:middle line:90%
>> Well-- or he'll leave.

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:20.550 align:middle line:90%
That's a really big one, but--

00:10:20.550 --> 00:10:21.530 align:middle line:90%
>> Or he'll get mad.

00:10:21.530 --> 00:10:22.330 align:middle line:90%
>> Get mad.

00:10:22.330 --> 00:10:23.000 align:middle line:90%
That's enough.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:23.800 align:middle line:90%
See?

00:10:23.800 --> 00:10:25.600 align:middle line:84%
Rejection, criticism,
withdrawal.

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:26.820 align:middle line:10%
Those are all scary things.

00:10:26.820 --> 00:10:28.570 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm afraid you're
not going to like me.

00:10:28.570 --> 00:10:28.900 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:29.520 align:middle line:90%
That's it.

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:30.320 align:middle line:90%
See?

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:32.590 align:middle line:84%
So what they do is,
they don't communicate.

00:10:32.590 --> 00:10:36.610 align:middle line:84%
And so what they have to do
is, we put that in perspective.

00:10:36.610 --> 00:10:38.788 align:middle line:90%
And we show that fear.

00:10:38.788 --> 00:10:40.580 align:middle line:84%
And then they're not
afraid to communicate.

00:10:40.580 --> 00:10:43.163 align:middle line:84%
>> So it's the worst thing-- you
think of the worst thing that

00:10:43.163 --> 00:10:47.080 align:middle line:84%
can happen as a result of
whatever you're going to do.

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:48.740 align:middle line:10%
And then you say,
I can handle that.

00:10:48.740 --> 00:10:49.540 align:middle line:10%
>> Yeah.

00:10:49.540 --> 00:10:52.028 align:middle line:10%
Once you've balanced it out
with what the opportunity is.

00:10:52.028 --> 00:10:53.320 align:middle line:10%
But that's the first technique.

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:54.945 align:middle line:84%
There's a second
technique we get into.

